1928 Sunday 1, January

Page Edit History:
  • aster.marie 06/28/2012 03:58 PM
  • psully 11/23/2010 03:38 PM

January Monday 2, 1928

Drove to Pasadena and back today to see the Standford-Pittsburgh game. Start at 8:45 A.M.- return at 11:45 P.M. A part cloudy but warm day. Hks, Allan, wife and I. 66 miles in the county (count north trip only.) Nothing seen.
Coming back heard loud Hyla regilla choruses at many points Noted San Mateo, San Onofre, Los Floras, Stuart, Oceanside, Carlsbad, Del Mar, La Jolla.

Saturday, January 14, 1928

Dos Cabezas

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 08/01/2012 04:57 PM

1928 Sunday 15, January

Returning from Chicago today via the S.D and A made the following notes on the Dos Cabezas section.

From the county line (Mp 112 Culvert B) to Dos Cabezas there is a long arm of desert rolling and sandy although much higher than the section around Coyote Wells. Much like the country just east of The Narrows. Plenty Ocatilla at MP111 we are 2 to 3 miles from the edge of the foot hills which lie to the South.

At Dos Cabezas we are still in the sandy area but the true foothills are very close. In fact Dos Cabezas may be said to be on the edge.

Above Dos Cabezas we see more grease wood and then plenty rocks.

After Dos Cabezas we again got out into a narrow sand-ocotilla area. The true gorge(Carrizo) begins at MP107+. Rocks close and in both side. The railroad does not follow Carrizo creek to the bottom. The creek goes off to the north.

Carrizo Gorge station (or siding) is way up the mountain at MP101. This is nowhere near the creek.

1928 Thursday 2, February

Feb 1
Drove to El Cajon for inspection of substations. Returned via the new Broadway(Bostonia) road over Fletcher hills and thence thru Rolando and the Chollas Road. A very clear day as warm as summer.

No snakes seen on the road alive or dead.

On Broadway h.w.y El Cajon hunted for a few moments in the rocks. Saw several Utas and Skellies. Found one yearling gopher coiled up under an old sheet scrap, was lively.

Total miles 35

February Sunday 19, 1928

Completed sorting and arranging my collection except several and juvenile amphibians.

Found amongst the Uta stansburiana 4 specimens of what appear to be Uta microscutata from San Diego Co and therefore the first from the U.S. I remember having been struck with these black Utas when collected at Jacumba.

February Wednesday 29, 1928

Went to Capistrano today at 8:30 A.M. to meet Guillow and Grunsky. Route Capistrano, El Toro(Junction) Serra, Laguna, Oceanside, Escondido, Home. Arrived at 5:45.
A moderately warm part cloudy day. Noted Hyla regilla croaking at San Clemente.
One juvenile gopher DOR at San Luis Rey.
Total miles in county 64+22+32=

Recd today from Tom Howley a fine large Aneides lugubris lugubris taken in a drain pipe at Lamont and Diamond, Pacific Beach.

Sunday, March 4, 1928

March Sunday 4, 1928

Today compared my specimens of Uta microscutata with those
sent down by Slevin.

I can find no important differences. My specimens all have
green throat patches compared with blue in the Lower Calif
specimens.

There is some evidence of difference in tail lengths, but I
do not consider this conclusive with so few specimens.

No Snout to anus Anus to tail tip Ratio
57441 40 83 2.07
57440 45 85 1.89
57436 40 68 1.70
57442 40 76 1.90
129 44 67 1.52
25 44 60 1.36
131 42 73 1.74

Monday, March 5, 1928

March Tuesday 6, 1928

Went to El Cajon Rotary club this noon with Holloway. A cloudy day after several rainy days.
28 miles. Nothing seen. Went and returned by Broadway extension.

Today I saw at the zoo a vicious Boyle's King from Las Flores. Vibrated the tail violently and struck the glass of the cage. Light rings were unusually dark. They were only about 3 scales wide at the mid dorsal line, widening to about 5 scales at the ventrals. The light rings were straw colored and as each light scale was surrounded by some dark skin the contrast usually in these snakes was still further reduced.

March Monday 12, 1928

Went to La Jolla this evening starting at 5:50. Dark Morena so didn't count. Saw nothing.

Received today from C.B Pertime 2 medium Scaphiopus hammondii taken yesterday at San Ysidro. Were dug out of fresh gopher mounds.

From Abbott the head of a C. exsul taken yesterday at Murry Dam by R.H. Goodrich and B.J. Carteri. Length 5'1" girth
9" rattles 16. Head too smashed to save.

Also from Abbott a C. ceractes fine specimen taken by A.A. Beaty ??? in Borego Valley 115 6 N.W. Cor lee.4.
Probably at Beaty ranch.

Tuesday, March 13, 1928

Went to El Cajon rotary club today. A cool part cloudy day. Went by way of University extension, returned by way of Magnolin extension, Helix, Lemon Grove and Broadway, extension. Saw nothing but on Uta. miles 35.

Drizzling rain tonight.

Friday, March 16, 1928

Went to Fowlers Wynola ranch with Chickering, Fowler, Pickham, Holloway. Started at 2 P.M.; returned at 6:30 P.M.
A fine clear day, dry, with north wind. Warm at low elevations, rather cool beyond Witch Creek. 119 miles. Went and returned by Broadway extension. Stopped only at Fowler's ranch where we hunted a few moments. No lizards seen.

1 Small gopher D.O.R. Riverview
1 Medium gopher D.O.R. Mussy grade 1/2 way up
1 large gopher D.O.R. near Sutherland Branch.

Saturday, March 17, 1928

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/24/2014 06:12 PM
  • tburress 03/23/2011 01:39 PM
  • psully 11/23/2010 03:38 PM

Sunday, March 18, 1928

Today went out to Carrizo stage station at the county line with Abbott. Started at 9:30 A.M. and arrived at about 4:30. Total distance (Union extension) 115.5 miles. A fine clear day. Quite warm on the desert side of the mountains.

Reached Julian at 11:35A.M. 63.3 miles.
1 horned toad noted at Ballena.
1 Large masticophis lateralis D.O.R top y
Santa ysabrel grade.
1 Uta A2. (send san felipe valley).
1 Uta A1 (box canon)
Noted many Utas from San Felipe all the way down. One Orcutti noted at box canon. Crot. Coll. baylii at S. end La Puerta. Callisaurus at Vallecito.
At Vallicitos picked up several H. regilla (A4-10) and one H.arenicolor (A3)
At Carrizo walked around the wash in the afternoon and picked up a few H.regilla. Went out on the mesa and got nothing. Got a small Sonora occ. under a piece of cardboard near the shed.
After supper took lanterns and went out in the was. Abbott got an unusually large Coleonyx. Ben went in the swamp and got many H.regilla and several Bufo douashalophilus. Hylas very plentiful and noisy.
Cold tonight. Couldn't keep blankets on.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/24/2014 06:12 PM
  • tburress 03/23/2011 01:55 PM
  • psully 11/23/2010 03:38 PM

1928, Monday 19, March

Carrizo stage station. Up at day break.
Couldn't sleep anyway b/c (??) cold. no use trying
to double blankets on a cot.
Went out hunting on the mesa (??) at 7:15. Still
cool but warming rapidly. Quite hot at 8:30.
Returned to camp at 9:15. Got Utas, 1 Callisaurus.
Saw plenty tracks in mesquite dunes
but was there too early. Saw plenty Utas
and a few Callys. Also maybe one Whiptail
but couldn't be sure. A11-14 Utas Carrizo; A15
Callisaurus.
Back at camp watched Utas nod.
Got a fine red race under a board at old
house. Was coiled.
The wash here is about 3 mi wide. Mixed
wash, plain and bad lands. Then higher hills
on each side. Plenty running water
Started back at about 11 AM. Quite hot. Saw
Callys and Utas opposite Agua Caliente. Got
Utas at the La Puerta (S. and A18-19) also a Skelly
Cutti? (??) (A20) Saw plenty Utas along here
also jar (??) Skallys (??) and Callys. Got Utas (A16-17)
at San Felipe, south end. Frogs eggs just laid
at Vallecato (??). Saw plenty Utas in Nammes (??) grade at east way up.
1 gantes DOR Faster haye (??)
1 " " Ruzrneir (??)
Home at 5:30 huntes 116 (Bdway ex)

March Tuesday 20, 1928

Recd (??) today 1 Red rattler large. hear
foot of bridle path, Torrey Pines.
1 Pacific rattler large,
J.F. Elliott, San Juan Hot Springs
(1 mi s.e.) Orange Co.

Recd on the 18th from Clyde Searl
1 small Phrynosoma m'calli (??) taken
at Carrizo.

Taking yesterdays trip as a whole I would
guess the season a little early for the desert
lizards except Utas. Although a few Callys
were seen they were not plentiful. Only one
doubtful Crem (??). 2 Crotaphytus collaris baylii
seen. No Dyesosaurus (??), no Crotaphytus tessellatus
tessellatus. Snakes on the desert were as
usual scarce. Looked hard for garters at Carrizo. negative

March Saturday 24, 1928

A drizzly rain set in at 3 P.M.
Went out to Mission Valley bridge at
5 P.M. for toads but found nothing.

Continued from Sunday 25th Mar.
This is not a particularly good place to
hunt as the creek is not still.
Wess (??) and the gang then left and Chuck
and I went down to the bridge halfway down
the Canon. Here we hunted. Got about 18
Hyla arenicolor; 4 Rana aurora draytonii
and 1 Hyla regilla. The Ranas were usually
in the water; but a large one that was too deep.
The H. arenicolors were both in the grass
and in the rocks. Most of them were taken on
the rocks where ont he shady shides they
were hiding in shallow crevices, cracks, dark
Ralches (??) etc. Got 4 in one shallow crack.
They Slalten (??) themselves against the granite
and match it closely. Some times they
are in shallow depressions where there are no cracks.
Caught a garter top of grade. Forgot to enter.

1928 Sunday 25, March

Went to Sentenae Canon today to meet Weiss and
Ranger's troop of Boy Scouts (who had gone out
Saturday afternoon and camped at foot of grade).
Went out alone; returned with Chuck Weiss.
Started at 8:30 A.M.; returned at 6 P.M. 157 miles.
Went regular road, University (??) extensions. Returned
same way. A cold windy day especially this
side of San Felyse. Had rained the night before.
Had to use chains on the Banner grade. hot
so wet coming back, but no day for lizards or
snakes.
On the way out saw 1 garter large D.O.R. at
Goose Valley junction. Coming back 1 Jursile (??) gopher
D.O.R. at Riverview. Except for these two and
a Skelly at foot of Banner grade no other lizards
or snakes were seen enroute.
Met Weiss and the scouts at top of sentenae (??)
about noon. Very windy. They had 1 garter (foot of
Sentenae), 1 Exsul fine light color (1 mi. east of
foot of grade) and 2 H. arenicolor (??) from forty grade.
We then proceeded to hunt at top of grade Weiss
on hill, balance in Creek. He got 2 live Orcuttis
a 1 Uta Stans (shot). We got about a dozen
H. regilla and 1 H. arenicolor in the creek.
Some of the former were females. Polywogs were
seen. (Continued under Saturday Mar 24)

*gopher snake from Jacumba April 5th. Counted

April Thursday 5, 1928

Went out this A.M. at 8:30, returned
to hotel at noon. Went to old Uta
mearnsi stamping ground about 3 mi east
of Jacumba. Very warm and comfortable
by noon.
Got 2 Uta microscutata, 3 Uta Stans,
1 Phryn. blainvillii, 1 large gopher snake. Did
some very rotten shooting. Saw plenty lizards
including Orcuttis, 2 mearusi and probabe,
1 Whip tail. Uta microscutata are in the
rocks and quite wary.
In the afternoon drove to the foot of H.S. grade.
Stopped several places between Jacumba and top
of grade. Utas were quite plentiful. Got 6 (492-7) and
1 Orcutti (491) Stomach contained yellow flowers, a worm
and what appeared to be a parasitic worm.
On the way down the mt. sp. grade saw 2 Chucks.
Hunted hard for about 2 hour in rocks at foot of grade.
Saw U. mearnsi, X. henshuir, and U. Stans but got nothing.
Hunted in old place on the way back, got me 1 Uta.
Saw no microscutata.
In the evening noted plenty B. b. halophylus and H. regilla
in almost dry swimming pool. Will catch later.
The uta microscutata when alure has lemon yellow throat
patch and brilliant blue green belly.
Miles in S.D. Co today 17. 22 intside *See under Apr 3d

1928 Friday 6, April

Today went to Oasis, Riverside County
and back. Started at 7:45; returned at
5. Total miles 228 of which only 17 were in S.D. county.
Was rather warm in Imperial County;
plenty warm for snakes and lizards.
Fig Tree John's is not in present highway being about 1 mi east.
On the way back stopped at
County line (Turpentine Rock) and walked
west about 2 mi probably into S.D. Co.
a half mile or more. Got 1 Uta Stans
(498) 2 Callys (499-500) and 2 Dysso (501-2)
Saw quite a few lizards including
2 Whiptails. No question about identification
Found Dyss stomachs full of flowers and
leaves.
On the way home stopped at a roadside
pond but Brawley and Imperial. Plenty
water bugs, showing permanency but no
polywogs.
One dead chuck on the mt. Spring; grade.
No snakes seen alive or dead although it
seemed an ideal day on the desert.

April Saturday7, 1928

Started out at 7:30 this AM and went
to usual place 2 mi east of Jacumba. Hunted
assiduously on both edges of the road until
noon. Got 1 Uta mearnsi (532) 4 Uta microscutata (521,
503-5) 6 Uta stans (506-11) and 1 Orcutti (512).
Saw plenty of Uta mearnsi in the usual place
on the rough granite rocks. Also saw 2 X. henshari (??)
here where results were negative last year. No doubt
as to identification as they were crushed moving a
rock. Saw many Orcutti including young. Uta mic
are usually seen on top of rocks especially
dark rocks. Seen to be more of a rock lizard
then Uta stans. Dont take refuge on the ground
so readily. Saw a large Masticophis lateralis
but lost him. A little windy in the morning
otherwise a perfect snake day.
In the afternoon went west about a mile.
Hunted hard on the rocks for nearly three hours.
Got 1 S. obesuatus, 1 Uta mic (514) and 6 Uta stans
(515-20) Also 6 X. henshauri alive.
Drove up the road to end of pairing and saw
2 yearling gophers DOR Boulevard. Total
miles today 26.
Went up to the bridge tonight to look for
amphibians. Nothing then but H. rigilla. Picked up
4 toads (B.b.h.) and 2 H.r. in the swimming pool. Could have
got many more if desired.

1928 Sunday 8, April

Started home from Jacumba at 8:30
a strong cold east wind blowing. No
day for reptiles.
Turned off to Tecote and hunted in
rocks. Too much wind. Got one X.h.
then gave it up. Started back and scared
up a large Masticophis lateralis crossing
the road. Stopped car quickly but lost
him in the rocks.
Turned up the Cottnwood about a
mile and got some polywogs (2 and
possibly three kinds) Also 2 small H. regilla
Stopped at top of Dulzura and hunted
in usual place. Strong wind still blowing.
Shot a small Skelly and in so doing scared
out a medium Mitchellii which had
just passed. Must have came very close to
him. Caught him OK. Encouraged by this I
worked hard in the rocks for an hour and
a half but didn't get another thing. Strong
wind still blowing. On the way home
noted the following. 1 M. lateralis large D.O.R. marilow
1 gopher small " "
1 red racer large " 28rBdway
arrived home at 2:10. Total miles 87.

April Monday 9, 1928

Recd today from L.H. Ross, Rencin.
San Felipe Wash Pole 732 Taken mau23
2 Red Racers (mating) and Pole 728
1 Spotted night snake. These poles are
near foot of Sentenae Canon - Yaqui
Well. Spotted night also mau23
Remove venom from 20 rattlers today.
11 fresh, 9 old.

With reference to colors of desert
animals:
Spotted night above is distinctly lighter
than average. lightest I have ever seen.
Uta at IV.E. Cov. of County very light.
Gopher from Jacumba as dark as
any annectens. Same for gophers from
La Puerta.
2 Red racers above are darker than
average. Red racer from Carrizo about
average for red phase.
Horned otad from Jacumba average
coloration.

Recd tonight a Sceloporus rufidorsum
from Abbott.

exsul; was on the more when first seen.

but cold at night.
Went out in the evening and got plenty
male H. regilla calling in a pond.

April Sunday 15, 1928

miles 000. A clear warm day; little wind.
Ideal for snakes.
First stop south of Oak Grove @ 12.7. Hunted
in rocks; got 2 large exsuls. Were sunning
themselves on a south ledge about 5 ft
apart. They were captured without difficulty.
No fight. Encouraged by this hunted hard

April Thursday 19, 1928

(May 7 continued)
He now proceeded to work his jaws toward
the head of the mouse after which he began
to swallow. Seemed to have most trouble with
head and hips, especially the latter. There were long waits without movement. After only the
tails was showing there were continued long
waits with the mouth open and no swallowing
movements. The tail finally disappeared - total
time since catching the mouse 29 min. We
then waited to see what it would do but it
was quite evident it was watching us
so we caught it. Retained the mouse when
we reached home.
Then proceeded to Mt. Springs. Stopped
part way down grade and got plenty tadpoles
large and small in shallow stream barely
flowing above ground. Probably anencolor.
Hunted for a while at the foot of the grade.
Got 1 Chuck in a rock crack but lost him. Got
1 Uta Mearnsi 635. Turned back at 103.8.
County line again at 109.9. Total miles Imperial Co.
11.9
Stopped for leaf mold and frogs but Clover
Flat and Campo. Reached home at 7:40. It
was dark at Indian Springs. Might have missed
snakes from then on. Miles today 147.3-11.9=135.4

April Wednesday 25, 1928

Today examined a very
conspicuously marked T.i. hammondii
from Hestor taken by B. Floerseh, April 24

The head above is polished olive green.
The back is olive green with black
spots which spots are unusually regular
and distinct. 3 series anteriously, 4
posteriourly to center of body, then three
again. Many are almost round. There
is an additional series on the sides in
the yellow.

April Sunday 29, 1928

In the morning the kids caught 4 small
Bufo Cognatus californicus hopping along by
the creek in loose sand. Plenty hylas reg.
heard the night before.
One dead garter in the creek. Another
was seen but not by me so cannot
count.
Hunted north east of the lodge from
8 to 11 AM with Chace, Johnstone and Weiss
(part time). Worked hard. Got 1 medium
Patch nose in adennortema and one medium
garter in creek. Saw several Whiptails
which could not be shot.
Got the following.
Skellys 611-615
Xantosiah 616
Orcutti 617
Uta Stans 618-624
Got one live horned toad and 1 small Skelly.
This was a perfect day and proper season;
and was much disappointed in both lizards
and snakes. Can only attribute this to
the quality of the granite boulders which
were soft. Virtually no flakes or cap
rocks. Tried both canons and ridges.

May Monday 7, 1928

Started out this morning from Pine Valley at
8:15. Cool and cloudy. Later clear. Rain in town.
First stop at usual pond Cottonwood Bridge 3 1/2
mi. S. of Buckmans. Plenty yearling californicus
hopping on the sand. Storr watched me dig in. I
dug one out. More today than last week. Plenty
tadpoles. Also got 3 arenicolor and uregilla. Got 2
Utas ivos 632-3. Saw orcuttis, skellys and 1 gerrhonotus.
Latter under bark of tree. Left here at 10:45 - now
sunny and warm.
Stopped east of Jacumba and had lunch -
then hunted south side of road for Utas. Got 1 Stans 634
No microscutata in sight.
Dr. Storr saw a medium red racer at
some distance; seemed to be watching something -
white footed mouse ran out of bush with snake
after it. Caught it in about 10 ft. Caught by
the middle and seemed to be killed by pressure
of the jaws. There was no constriction, nor any
pressure by the body. After holding for a few
moments the snake glided to the shade of a
Juniper carrying the mouse with head well
up about 6" off the ground. In the brush he
had his body in this shape
(continued page April 19)

1928 Monday 14, May

long fangs for its size and gives plenty
of venom. Has small scales between
anterior nassal and rostral but this does
not prevent contact.
No venom from 2 specimens of C. tigris
1 large exsul had white venom. Had
been milked before.
1 Mitchellii had the anterior nasal
in contact with the rostral although the
usual row of small scales had partly
separated them. 2 others from Daggett
were fully in contact.

cendre blue fading to Venice green posteriorly
First male light greenish yellow edged with

Young male throat strontian yellow; belly
brennen blue. Large male with end of tail off.

Went to Mt. Springs and hunted about

May Wednesday 23, 1928

In color it is decidedly more like
T. lyrophanes than T. randenburghi.
The body color is light gray; the
spots are light brown. The head is
lighter than any T. randenburghi I have
seen. Altogether it looks like the
Lower Cal. specimens from the U.S. N.M.
Body spots 34; tail spots 17. The count of
body spots is not very definite as many of
the secondaries go clear across and others
are indefinite.
Anal undivided. Scale rows 1" back
of head 21; at mid body 23 near 15
ventrals 129 Probably M C 7 U com.
The ventrals are quite white. The
primaries and secondaries engage
the edge of the ventrals.
Supralabials R8L8 Lower 12L10 Preoculars
R4? L3 Post occulars R? L3. Temporals
cant be determined b/c damage to specimen
Subloveal present in left; not clear
on right b/c damage.

1928 Saturday 26, May

Went to "Wings." Pickled specimens.

Notes on a live Tiger Rattler. One of
the two from C.L. Evans.
The cross stripes are brown formed of
a multiplicity of dark dots. The light
stripes between are pinkish gray
lighter on the sides. The colors are
darker anteriorly than posteriorly and
the stripes are less distinct. The iris
is yellow, the pupil vertical and very
small in bright light. The head is
unusually small. The color below
is orange pink mottled with darker.

1928 Wednesday 30, May

Went out with C. Searl today. Started
at 8:40; returned at 8:30. Cool and cloudy
on the coast; warm and pleasant in the
back country; cool in the mountains; hot
and windy in the desert.
Total miles 273; miles in San Diego County
185; miles to be counted 145 as the east 40
miles were in darkness and snakes could
not have been seen.
Route Univ. Extension, Lakeside, Julian, Sentenae,
Borega P.O. Kane Springs, West Moreland, Imperial,
near El Centro, Jamacha, Pine Valley, Willows,
La Mesa, Bdway Extension.
Hunted in sandy and rocky wash beyond the
Narrows for 40 minutes after lunch. Quite hot. Nothing
seen but Utas and they in the shade. Along
the road from Yaqui Well to Borega saw Callys
and Dips perched in rocks. The Callys stand
high with stiff legs. Also saw Utas
and Whiptails but the latter were not perched
on rocks. Took 1 Dip, several Utas and Callys.
This the only place where we hunted.

June Saturday 2, 1928

Went out this afternoon
with C. Pearl. Started at 1:30; returned
at 5:45. Cloudy in town, clear and
pleasant in the back country.
Univ. Extension, La Mesa, Bostonia,
Suncrest, Bostonia, Hillsdale, Jamacha,
Bdway Extension. 55 miles.
Hunted only at one point namely
Suncrest. Hunted in rocks burned
over probably last year. Lizards except
Xantusias were scarce. Got 1 Uta
and 1 Skelly. 14 Xantusias alive.
Lost probably an equal number. Think
this indicates Xantusia through their
life habits are better able to withstand
fire than the others. Was surprised to
note Xantusias under caps as frequently
as under flakes. Sometimes flat caps. Once
a flat and dirty flake.
1 Garter DOR Radio S. Medium Creek (dry).
1 Gopher DOR Radio S. Large Brush.
1 Gopher DOR Radio S. Medium Grass.
Only snakes seen were on Broadway Extension.

Notes:

lwilliams

C. Pearl or C. Searl??

Went out today with C. Searl. Started at
9AM.; returned at 6:15. Cloudy along the coast
(to Poway summit) clear and comfortably cool
in the back country. Route. Murphy Canon, Escondido,

1928 Thursday 7, June

Went to Los Angeles today with
Weiss. A cool cloudy day. Miles
in the county 59.1. Total miles 130. Went
via Rose Canon, Seal Beach and Norwalk.
Arizona elegans L La Costa 32.3 Fields DOR
Red racer L La Costa 34.2 Fields DOR
Cal King. L Solana Beach Fields DOR
Cal King L Las Flores 48.2 Fields DOR.
Cal King s bet L. S. Onofre 54.3 Fields + Brush DOR
In the evening went to a "specimen night"
meeting of the Herpetological Society of Calif.
Took 13 jars of specimens. Was not as interesting
a meeting as it might have been because of
the method of conducting. Did not have
an adequate chance to see the other's specimens.
Bogert showed me a small Trimorphodon from
an unknown source. Also said there was
one in the collections of the Lincoln High School.
Hill told me his museum had recently
received a Trimorphodon (from Temecula) and
a Phyllophynchus (from Palin Springs).
Saw Colburns Clarion bland Racer.
Saw a Ph. platyrhinus from Independence.
(not a new locality ride Van Renbrugh).

1928 Thursday 21, June

Longest Day
Recd today from Searl a large
Boyle's King taken at Fallbrook and
a Triturus torosus taken in Boulder
Creek.
This afternoon went out with
Miss Atsatt, Searl and a party
of instructors from U.C.L.A. Started
at 2 P.M.; returned at 6:30 P.M.
Univ. Ext. Bostonia, Suncrest, La Mesa,
Imperial Ave. 51 miles x no snakes
seen on the road.
Stopped at studio near Grossmont
and got 5 X.h. Next stop at Suncrest.
got 30 X.h.. Also 1 med. red rattler.
Saw Skellies and 1 Eurmeces on a rock.
This was about 5 P.M.
This evening put the rattlers in a Zoo
box with a large Boyle's King. Both
indicated clearly a strained attitude; the
rattler by almost continuously rattling and
the King by rigidity and a loop
up at the end of the cage.

June Sunday 24, 1928

Started out this AM at 9 o' clock for
Roane Valley taking along Milt. Bailey's kid
Steve as guide. Went through the upper
Doane Valley to edge of lower where road
stopped. Returned by main road. Got back
at 12. Clear and moderately warm. Total
miles 6.0. Smashed running board
box and damaged both running boards
b/c of rocks on road side.
In Doane valley the lizard business was
excellent. There was much old lumber lying
about and under these Utas and Skinks
were plentiful. Got 5 of each alive and lost
plenty. Also lost one snake of which only
the tail was seen. Was under a board. Think
it was either a garter or a young Western yellow
belly. Also lost one garter in the creek which
Ditras thought had a central dorsal stripe
but this was by no means certain. Maj. Grant
caught 3 T.o. hammondii in the creek. One
Hyla was seen.
Skelly's were plentiful on rocks and stumps.
Shot 11. Also 5 Utas. Was in pines only
a little way.
Started for home at 1:30 went via East Grade,
Henshaw, Rincin, Pala, Escondido, Murplay Canon.

1928 Friday 29, June

(Thursday July 5 continued)
The Hylas were in boulders along
the stream bend both in the stream
and in the sides. Not in crevices but rather
in indentations. Sometimes 3 to a boulder.
All in the shade.
The water dogs were very plentiful
both in side pools and in the main
stream. They were more easily caught
in the former. Only 3 or 4 were on land;
these were quite close to water. They hide
under rocks or in the mud when
disturbed.
Got 1 Juvenile rattler at Cuyamaca
on the road at 6:15 P.M.

July Wednesday 4, 1928

Worked on statistical data in the
morning.

At 1:30 P.M went to pond on
Cottonwood below Buckenan's. Walked
up the creek which is dry except for
a few pools; then down the main
river.
Many young Hyla regilla were
seen and a few young Hyla arenicolor.
Also 1 adult of each. Collected adults
and a few young. Saw 2 Rana
Aurora draytonii but did not collect.
No toads of any kind were seen.
(compare with last year)
Collected 1 Uta 1 Skelly. Others
were seen. Saw 2 Skinks and 2
Orcutti. 1 Skink was under a
rotten log. Collected but lost him. Got him again.
Returned at 4:15 No snakes
seen. Total miles 18.
Lizards are certainly scarce at
this time of year.
Some pollywogs were seen just
ready to change. Collected a few.
Hyla arenicolor, Uta stans and Skelly have mites.

July Friday 6, 1928

Worked up statistics this
morning.
In the afternoon went to Pine Valley
Creek Bridge and walked down stream
from there. Walked slowly and worked
carefully. Went down about 1/2 mile
Saw four garter snakes of which

midstream with head out where current
was swift and he was acting as
cut water.

found when piece was broken off.

Saw one Skelly under a dead log.
Lizards very scarce although day
was not hot.

seen in side pools.

1928 Monday 9, July

Have a bad cold today; not feeling
good. Did considerable statistical work.

July 11th continued
They take refuge under logs, in logs
and in ground holes but particularly
under logs. Most of the specimens we
got were scared out but a few were seen
both on stones and on logs. Their uniformity
of size and marking makes their identification
certain.
Also at this point (where we turned
over many logs) got one tailless Eusatina
croceate in the center of a rotting log
amongst all the punk.
Next went to the lake where Phil
got a medium garter on the shore.
I turned over many logs but it was
too late for lizards.

  • rwpan 02/18/2013 06:45 PM

July Tuesday 10, 1928

Went to Laguna Mountain with
Phil, Gartz and Reeves. Start at 10 AM;
back at 1 P.M. 34 miles. Clear day.
Warm at Pine Valley cooler on the
mountain.
Nothing seen on the road except
a couple of Utas and Skellys about
1/2 way up.
Only hunted one place namely
at the Laguna at the end of
the road. Here got 2 small Hyla
regilla (spoiled), 4 Skellies*, and
2 T.o. hammordii. Saw several additional
Skellies, 2 Skinks (which were lost)
and at least 8 additional garters. Where
were lost. Garters were in fact quite
common but hard to catch whether in
the grass around the lake or in a
pile of rocks close by the side of the lake.
Lifted many small rocks around this rock
pile and nearly every one had 2 or 3
shed skins underneath. Never saw so
many shed skins.
Every Skelly has red lice. Small garter
contained Hyla tadpole - frog (tail + legs) and
a black worm? *S. g. vandenburgianus

1928 Wednesday 11, July

This morning at 9:30 went to Buckmans,
Campo, White Eagle (New Town) and back
to Pine Valley. Total distance 53. Returned
at 12:30. A rather hot day.
Stopped at pond on the Cottonwood for
a few moments. Noted 2 Ranas, 1 Hyla
regilla. Collected 1 Uta, 1 Skelly and
1 Whiptail. The whip and the Uta have
lice. The Skelly has worms (saved some)
Got a Whiptail at Clover flat. Saw
a young orcutti 4 mi w. of White Eagle.
No snakes seen alive or dead. Whiptails
seem to be the only lizards abroad and
active on a hot day. While they do not
deliberately stay in the sun they dont
seem to avoid it particularly.
This afternoon at 2:30 with Searl, Nation,
Phil and Reeves went to Laguna. Returned at 6:30.
35 miles. First stop about half way up.
Saw one Uta. Next stop on south end of mountain
Got one S.g. vandenburgianus. Next stop about
halfway bet ranger station and lake.

was seen) and seven s.g. vandenburgeanus.
These are found under boards and
are caught with some difficulty (continued on July 9)

1928 Friday 13, July

Went to Laguna this afternoon with
Gartz, Reeves and Phil. Started at 2 P.M.;
returned at 5:30. 29 miles. A hot day
in Pine Valley; cooler on the mountain.
Hunted assiduously at 2 points on
the mountain, turning over logs etc.
Got 1 Scelopones oecidentalis beseriatus
F, 3 skinks (lost several) and
7 male and 11 female Sceloporus graciosus
vandenburgranus which is what we
went after. They are quite common but
not easy to catch. They are just seen on
logs, stumps or rocks. When frightened
they take refuge under logs usually
but also under stones, in ground holes
or even in leaves or pine needles (when
run down) Two were noted to run up
trees. They are very quick and active
and difficult to catch unless they become
intangled in the grass.
Saw a few miscellaneous lizards on
the way down.
Went to Ryans store but saw
nothing 5:30 - 6:30 15 miles.
No snakes seen today, dead or
alive.

July Sunday 22, 1928

This morning, a moderately cool

With Philip. 75 miles.
One C. oreganus large DOR at

Got 1 young S. orcutti. Not too hot

out at midday at this time of year.
At top of Mt. Spring's grade (Boulder

usual way. Rather a rocky place for
a Cally.

in daylight. Nothing seen.

1928 Tuesday 31, July

Several days ago Slain told

in damp sawdust to try to
hatch. She probably laid more
but the garter must have eaten
them. Saw she was about to lay
one but in the evening there was
no egg there.

August Wednesday 1, 1928

Went to Pine Valley this
afternoon at 4; arriving at 6.
A moderately cool day. Via El Cajon
Ave and Old Viejas Grade. Returned

(Aug 5 continued from Aug 2) They are
more plentiful than on Laguna and larger
(unless all there taken on elaguns were
juveniles) They take refuge under boards,
in cracks in logs and in cracks in rocks.
They seem quicker than S.ob. which are
present in the same locality.
Many tiny Utas were seen.

Page Edit History:
  • rwpan 02/20/2013 06:09 PM

1928 Thursday 2, August

(August 5 continued). and put in over
four hours in hard hunting. Got plenty
more Ranas including some very small ones.
A medium C.Oreganus, an ensatine and
good seve's of Eunesces, Uta stans, Skellies
and gracusus.
The rattler was on a shelf in heavy grass
on the creek bluff. He rattled as we
passed below. He was found to have opaque
eye corenug's (just changing. The ensatine
was found in a rotting log.
Returned to the car, had supper and then
walked to Bailey's where we arrived at 7:45.
Total miles today 16, no snakes on the road.
Rana boylii muscosa is less wary than
R.a.d. and far more easy to catch. It is
usually on the banks although occasionally
found in the water. GOt some very small ones
and saw a couple of tadpoles that may be
this species. The pools are not deep and
the frogs could not escape as does R.a.d.
Occasionally they took refuge in the water
but many times tried to escape in land by
getting under overhangs, roots etc.
Gracious was found especially on
logs, although also on rocks and in bushes.
(To aug 1st)

August Friday 3, 1928

Talked to Taylor concerning his
desert trip Tuesday to Thursday. He
got 4 C. cerastes on the desert near
Master City, Imperial County. He hunted
until nearly midnight. 2 were coiled
up; 2 were crawling around. Also
he got a small boa D.O.R. at Boulder
Park, San Diego County. Got 3 Arizonas
near Plaster City at night. 1 Mitchelli
medium at Boulder Park.
Got Ranas at Kitchen creek and
a garter at Buckmans. On the previous
trip he got several garters at Kitchen creek.
Count only the first one above mentioned.

Continued from Aug 4th.
The latter were both in the stream and in sand;
probably more in the river. Got at least 3 fine
adults. These were taken about half protruding
from pockets in the sand of the river bed probably
just emerging. A couple of Utas were also taken on the sand.
No snakes on the road today, alive or dead.

1928 Saturday 4, August

Started for the Pala Camp with Dr. E.H. Taylor,
Wm. hunceford, Searl, Weiss and 3 kids at
2 P.M. Went via Escondido, Valley Center and
Cole grade. Arrived at 6 P.M. Distance (including
evening drive) 76 miles. A cool day for summer.
First stopped at Valley Center and hunted
here quite a while. Got Uta Stans, Skellies,
hyla regilla, Rana a. d. and bufo b.h.
Saw one garter snake in the creek but lost
him. Looks like a good hunting ground along
the creek. The bufos were in an old well.
The rocks here are poor for Xantusias.
Next stopped at the San Luis Rey River
crossing at the foot of Cole Grade. Collected
Bugo cognatus calif., both hylas, Rana a.d.
Uta stans and skellies. The bufos seemed
to be of 2 vintages, this years and last.
Most of them were found hopping along at the
food of a sand bank. Although a few were
picked up elsewhere. The hylas seemed half
grown. A few tadpoles were seen.
After supper went back to the same place
and collected hard with flashlights and
lanterns from about 7:30 to 10:30. Got hylas,
young ranas (the smallest I have ever taken)
and plenty Bufo cognatus californicus (cont to aug 3rd)

Sunday, Aug. 5, 1928

Started for the camp at 6:30 for Doane Valley going direct by Nigger Canyon grade, Moderately cool with high fog. Stopped briefly 2 or 3 times on the grade but collected nothing On the way up saw Uta stans, skellies and a whip.

First stop at Silver Creek which is at the top of the mountain toward the west end. Had fine collecting here amongst the rocks getting many skellies, Uta stans, Graciosas and 3 whiptails.

Stopped at 2 or 3 more points on the way to Doane Valley and got more of the same. Taylor saw one snake in the grass which was lost before it could be identified.

Just at the entrance to Doane Valley broke the bottom of the gas tank and lost all the gas. Took off the tank (a long hard job) and sent it back to town with Weiss, Searl and the kids. They started just after lunch.

Taylor and Kunceford hunted while we were taking off the gas tank and got the usual lizards (no whips ) and a fine series of Rana boylii muscosa.

After lunch we went down to the foot of the valley and back (Continued to Aug. 2)

Monday Aug 6, 1928

This morning at 8:30 we started back from Bailey's to Doane Valley

Taylor had previously gone out at 5 AM and got 2 Ensatinas under bark, a large and a small. I went out around the barn from 6:30 to 7:30 but saw nothing.

Along the way between Baileys and Doane Valley we got a good collection of lizards, Uta stans, skelly, graciosus and skinks. Also I saw one large banded racer in a bush but lost him. Further on Lunceford and I found a fresh track in the road and then Lunceford spied a large banded racer in the brush. He was coiled about 3 ft. above the ground and ten feet away from the road. Shot him.

Savage had arrived and fixed the car by 10:30. We walked down the creek and got more lizards and a good series of R. b. m.. I saw a Western yellow belly but lost him. We caught one large garter.

Had lunch by the old shack and started back at 2:15 having hunted continuously from 8:30 to 1:15. The graciosus were not as plentiful as in the late afternoon

(Continued to Jul 23d)

Tuesday, Aug. 7, 1928

Saw Taylor to say good bye this afternoon. He collected on Grossmont today and got about 25 Xantusia, Henshawi and a Trimorphodon.* The latter was under a flake. He will lend it to me. Also he will send me a Bufo punctatus, S. jarrovi and other items.

He also told me he had taken B. c. e. at Kitchen ( Cottonwood Creek ) and found a B. b. h. amongst the toads taken at Cole Grade Crossing Saturday night.

*Contained a Xantusia henshawi

October 22, 1928. Examined the above specimen loaned to me by Taylor.
Scale Rows 23 Ventrals 240 and entire Caudales 66 complete F. Supras 8-9 Lufras 12-12 Preoc 3-36 Patoe 3-3 Loreals 3-3 (2+1) Lareals 3+4, 3+3 Spots 40+15

Colors normal. Blotches even Splits not very clear.

Sunday, Aug. 19, 1928

Went to Coronado Islands today with Weiss, Grant, Hertlein, Searl, Phil and Sanger's troop of Boyscouts.

Landed only on South Island. Landed at 11:30, left at 2:30. A clear cool day; some fog in the distance.

Hunted well toward the north end of the ridge and south as far as the low place. Got 2 Uta stansburiana hesperis, 2 skinks, 2 Gerrhonotus scincicauda webbie and 4 whiptails. All but the skinks had orange mites. The whips seem to feed on grasshoppers judging by stomach contents of one.

Lost a number of whips and 1 large skink. Saw 2 rattlesnake skins under rocks.

The whips and alligators are in the low brush on the ridge. The skinks are under rocks. The utas are low down. The whips seem to be the most plentiful and are of good size. The last skink was large. The only 2 alligators taken were half size on a mainland basis.

Sunday, Sept 9, 1928

Spent 3:30-5:3 with Hill at LA Museum.

Checked over 2 Arizona atrox and about 6 California oreganus.

Found definite verifications of C. cerastes and S. humulii in Los Angeles County.*

Noted the following specimens:
Trimorphodon vandenburghi no. 133 J. Hornung Temecula, 4-6-28. Usual dark brown; anal undivided, dorsal spots 37; tail spots 16, incomplete.

Phyllorhynchus decurtatus No. 491 J. Hornung Palm Springs 4-16-28

There is much in this collection that would be interesting to check over although it has been rather poorly kept and is now badly arranged. There is considerable unidentified material and also much without labels.

La Museum #234 Antelope Valley
both checked OK.

Monday Sept. 10, 1928

This morning went over to see Weinbrug at 1:20 N. Gates St., L.A.

He had a interesting lot of stuff but the locality records are not kept so that it loses value. However he gave me a young scutulatus(?) and a large phyllorynahus both definitely from Inyo Kern ( Kern Co. ) and loaned me several sidewinders for milking from the same place.

I saw a very dark red racer from somewhere in Calif and likewise a king snake L g b with light rings as narrow as any eastern Chain snake.

He had several oreganus (one unusually exlack) a large scutulatus and a peculiar Oreganus about halfway between the great basin and the California Type. But as he didn't know where any of these were from they wre useless as specimens.

Learned that Australia blue tailed skinks will eat snails, chuckawallus will eat watermelon, sidewinders, lizards, oreganus dead gophers when they wont touch rats.

Went out to see Rowe at San Fernando. He gave me a very interesting account of having been bitten seriously by an oreganus 5 weeks ago.

(Continued to Sept. 7)

Wednesdlay, Sept. 12, 1928

Milked snakes this noon.

Started from S.D. with Weiss at 3:30. A medium cool day. Went to Los Angeles via Rose Canyon and Long Beach. Miles county 58. One dead snake on the road at San Onofre. Traveling too fast to stop (next evening it was gone).

Visited Tex Schubach's snake show at Long Beach. He has a good collection of atrox mostly from Arizona. He is a little indefinite as to localities but knows that he has had them from Bakersfield, Mesa and Coleridge, Ariz.. Noted that the supra ocula dashes were missing on most yet on Texas specimen has strong dashes.

He has 2 good specimens of scutulatus from Globe, Ariz.

He has a fine albino gopher from Torrance Calif. about 3 ft. long. Says there was another smaller one which got away. The parietals are, as usual in albinos, distorted. The eyes are pink. The normal yellow is light yellow. The bloc brown or red is white.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/23/2014 10:36 PM
  • pamg 02/23/2014 10:36 PM

Thursday, Sept. 13, 1928

Spent an hour in the LA Museum thi afternoon. Checked up Phyllorphynchus and a couple of lizards.

Returned the sidewinders to Weinberg this AM. Gave him a turtle and a red rattler.

Saw Schubach again this evening. He had just unpacked one shipment from Randolph, Ariz and another for Florence, Ariz.

Saw a large scutulatus form Randolph (243). Usual contrasting tail. The largest scutulatus I have ever seen. Color green brown. truncated diamonds. There were in this shipment 6 atrox from M to L. an 2 scutulatus 1 L 1 S. He gave me the latter. No doubt as to locality; was on the box.

Altogether he had 5 scutulatus all were 2 scales but supra oculars.

The other shipment from Florence, Ariz contained 1 scutulatus in about 12 atrox. Absolutely no difficult in distinguishing.

Nothing seen on the way home in the dark. Arrived at 10 P.M.

Sunday, Sept 16, 1928

Worked all day checking U.C. crotalus specimens and pickling 11 snakes

The King snake eggs I put up some weeks ago were examined today and found shriveled and dead.

Put a small scutulatus in the warm (not hot) sun in a glass jar. Got very violent. Rattled continuously. Breathed with great rapidity. Struck at everything.

I note that whenever a snake is skinned prematurely some of the scales even in normally dark areas lack pigment an are nearly white. This may account for some light colored specimens in collections. Also for the queer light spots.

Page Edit History:

Recd 60 specimens from U.S.N.M. today.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/23/2014 11:14 PM

Saturday, Oct. 6, 1928

Went to Yuma today with L. B. Jones, Alford Fisher and Abbott. Started at 2:30 P.M. Arrived at 10:10 P.M. A moderately warm day. About 90 in the Valley.

No stops were made in the county and no snake were seen alive or dead. Went out via Broadway extension and old Viejas grade. Miles in county 90. Total miles 190.

Stopped for 15 minutes at Coyote Wells at 5:00. Got one Uta stans. Jones got a Red Racer by the tail but lost him when he twisted the end off. Never saw this done before. I saw him once. Was the yellow brown phase.

Got to El Centro at 6:30. Dined at Barbara Worth.

Got a small gopher DOR 7 mi. E. of El Centro (call it Holtville ). Good enough to save as a specimen.

Got s large sidewinder crossing the road at 6 mi beyond Holtville. We must have run over him as he was dead next morning.

One small sidewinder DOR 8 mi. beyond Holtville.

Hunted several places in the desert with flash lights but had no luck.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/23/2014 11:47 PM
  • psully 11/23/2010 03:38 PM

Sunday, Oct 7, 1928

Started back this AM at about 9:30. Was warmer today. At El Centro they said it was warmest day in two weeks.

1 small Patch nose DOR at 7 mi. W. of Yuma. Saved him.

Hunted for about 2 hours in the sandhills at a point 17 mi. W. of Yuma. Good luck here. Got 24 uma notada, 23 Uta graciosa and 2 Dips. Also 1 small sidewinder.

The Umas are quite plentiful but difficult to shoot. They don't stop on the edge of a bush like Callys, but run into it and behind it and then hid in the sand or go down a hole. They are very fast. The utas are on bushes as usual. The sidewinder was in the shade of a bush.

A very light colored Patch nose DOR at 22 mi. W. of Yuma.

Hunted for a short time 31 mi. W. of Yuma. Got 1 Uta graciosa (1510) and a Leopard lizard.

Lunched at El Centro until 2:30.

Hunted 15 mi. West of El Centro bet Dixieland and Plaster City. Got 4 Callys. Saw uta stans and whiptail.

1 Red Racer DOR 5.5 mi. East of Mt. Springs Co line. First from Imp. Co.

Home at 7:30. Miles today 188. Count 37 miles in county while light. Nothing seen.

Wednesday, Ovct. 24, 1928

Drove to LA today via Rose Canon with Jacobson. A clear warm day Nothing seen. 60 miles in county. Also went to La Jolla in the morning. 30 miles.

Visited Tex Schubach's place at Long Beach in the evening for about 40 minutes.

He had several items of interest A King snake of the getulus group said to have been taken near Flagstaff, Ariz. Looked like a Eastern King.

Also a Tiger Rattler said to have been taken at or near "Petrified Forest" Calif?, evidently some place out on the Mojave. Seemed lighter than Arizona specimens and possibly with a larger head.

He gave me a young Oreganus from Florence, Ariz.

Checked his scutulatus (19) and atrox (32) and made notes thereon for my study.

Tuesday, Dec. 4, 1928

This morning at 7:30 started for Riverside arriving at 10:40. Returned 1:30 to 4:30. Miles in county 140.

It had rained for two nights and one day before, although today as clear. There must have been many toads out last night as many had been run over the night before not withstanding presumably light traffic. Could have got many locality records if I had stopped on the way up but business prevented. On the way back few bodies were left and these were so dry as to make identification difficult.

Checked one spade foot at County line, Rainbow.

One juvenile Gopher DOR at 11, Rosedale. Fresh.

Lampropeltis getula

California King snake

L.g. boylii refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a ringed pattern.

L.g. californiae refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a striped pattern.
